BugPattern.ShortDescription: More arguments are passed than are actually used in the format string
BugPattern.Details: A format-string method with a variable number of arguments is called, but more arguments are passed than are actually used by the format string. This won't cause a runtime exception, but the code may be silently omitting information that was intended to be included in the formatted string.

Found a call to a method which will perform a byte to String (or String to byte) conversion, and will assume that the default platform encoding is suitable. This will cause the application behaviour to vary between platforms. Use an alternative API and specify a charset name or Charset object explicitly.

BugPattern.ShortDescription: The type of a supplied argument doesn't match format specifier
BugPattern.Details: One of the arguments is uncompatible with the corresponding format string specifier. As a result, this will generate a runtime exception when executed. For example, String.format("%d", "1") will generate an exception, since the String "1" is incompatible with the format specifier %d.

BugPattern.ShortDescription: Method invokes inefficient new String(String) constructor
BugPattern.Details: Using the java.lang.String(String) constructor wastes memory because the object so constructed will be functionally indistinguishable from the String passed as a parameter.  Just use the argument String directly.
